 traditional (ontological) view vs. a transcendental one (Rosiak) there follow two sections: the first presents studies of substance as showing some causal aspects (Buchheim, Keinänen, Kovac, Piwowarczyk), whereas the other contains investigations of causality showing in a way its reference to the category of substance (Kobiela, Meixner, Mitscherling, Wroński). The last, short section contains two studies ofextension (Leszczyński and Skowron) which can be regarded as a conceptual background of both substantiality and causality. The book gives a very colourful picture of the discussions connected with substantiality and causality which may be of potential interest for the readers.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCausation. 0aSubstance (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Logic.2bisacsh  aCausality.  aCommon Cause Principle.  aSubstantiality.1 aBuchheim, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeinänen, Markku, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKobiela, Filip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKovač, Srećko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeszczynski, Damian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeixner, Uwe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitscherling, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiwowarczyk, Marek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosiak, Marek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosiak, Marek, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSkowron, Bartłomiej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSzatkowski, Miroslaw, eeditor